PowerShell Overview:

PowerShell is a command-line interface used for managing computers and automation tasks. It is especially useful for performing bulk operations that would be cumbersome through a graphical interface.

Cmdlet:
Cmdlets are the commands used in PowerShell.

Modules:
Modules contain cmdlets and functions.

Opening PowerShell:
- Start -> PowerShell
- Start -> PowerShell ISE: Used for writing long scripts.

Examples of PowerShell commands:
- Get-Service: Retrieves services (similar to services.msc)
- Get-Service -name <serviceName>: Retrieves a specific service.
- Get-Service -name <serviceName> | Stop-Service: Stops a service.
- Get-Service -name <serviceName> | Start-Service: Starts a service.
- Get-ADUser -Filter *: Retrieves all users in Active Directory (AD).
- Get-ADUser -Filter {name -like "<name>*"}: Retrieves a specific user.
- Get-ADUser -Filter * -SearchBase "<distinguishedName>": Retrieves users or OUs at the specified address.
- Get-ADUser -Filter * -SearchBase "<distinguishedName>" | Set-ADUser -City "<city>": Changes the city information for users at the specified address.
- Get-Module -ListAvailable: Shows available modules in PowerShell.